experience.description:
In telecommunications, gigahertz signals are applied to the radar system and petahertz is employed in optical communications. Between these two frequencies, terahertz (THz) field still has plenty of potential to explore. In recent years, analysis of material properties by THz systems has reached increasing advances, in which THz spectroscopy allows optical properties to be determined as function of frequency.

I conducted research on signal processing of THz transient passing through Single Walled Carbon Nanotube (SWCNT) sample in THz time domain spectroscopy system. Our team processed signals to measure properties of sample material, including refractive index, conductivity, absorption coefficient, and dielectric constant. In the research, I proposed optimization techniques applied to lower noises in spectroscopy to the group. The optimal methods were adapted to facilitate calculation of material properties and the research results were demonstrated in Undergraduate Research Poster Expo.

experience.title: Research Assistant

experience.description:
As an intern at Localization and Pose Estimation Service group, I worked on online sensor calibration and nonlinear joint optimization. Considering the sensors installed on trucks, it's hard to "measure" real extrinsic parameters between an IMU and another sensor; so we designed a tool, which adopts a SLAM-like way to do online calibration.

I implemented a framework for generating optimized extrinsic transformation between a perception sensor and IMU. This can be applied on both Camera-IMU and LiDAR-IMU calibration. Backend includes IMU preintegration, LiDAR/Camera constraints and extrinsic optimization, which are implemented using G2O framework; frontend adopts point cloud plane extraction, grouping and matching.
experience.title: Intern

experience.description:
This project is completed under the support of Google Summer of Code 2018 program. In nearly three months, I contributed to a better user-interface for a Robot perception system, called RoboSherlock. The specific work is as follows:

1. Reorganized an APACHE library, called UIMACPP, from autotool-built project to a ROS-CMake project, so that it can be released as a debian ROS package. This library is for knowledge management, which is a necessary dependency for RoboSherlock.
2. Investigated some error scenarios and added necessary error handlers for backend UIMA library. 
3. Migrated xml-based analysis engine input to yaml-based analysis engine input for RoboSherlock, so that users don't need to take care of complex structure, instead RoboSherlock will automatically do.

summary:
I love robotics.

Ever since taking my first robotic course and seeing how robots work in real world situations, I have been obsessed with the idea of using robots to solve real world problems. Robotics Engineering is a role that I am passionately engaged in pursuing. I believe robots can improve and transform the lives of people around the world.

For my first professional experience, I was given the opportunity to be a research assistant in Assistive Robotics Group at National Chiao Tung University. My role was to implement obstacle avoidance using q learning with OpenAI Gym, establish object recognition using AlexNet, and design a motion planning algorithm for our unmanned surface vehicle. However, working on and learning about these subjects was not enough to sate my curiosity.

This passion has carried me to continuing my education at UCSD. Here I have more resources available to me. I have the opportunity to take courses such as artificial intelligence, statistical learning, and fundamentals of machine learning. While the courses are tough, I'm still enthusiastically grasping those concepts. Since it is here that I learned truly how much I still have to learn.

Now, I am looking for 2020 robotics/machine learning engineering summer internships to further my knowledge and practical experience.

experience.description:
Currently, commercially available power wheelchairs may not be affordable by low income families especially in developing countries. Moreover, these don't have computers and sensors on-board to enable smart safety behave to aid navigation. The UC San Diego Smart Open Source Wheelchair will deliver an affordable modular design that can be replicated around the world and used as a testbed for future development in healthcare safety for patient that requires use of wheelchairs. 

We are a team of undergraduate students with a goal of designing a smart wheelchair that can potentially change the lives of many people who struggle with permanent debilitating diseases that cause mobility and motor control. This research is lead by Ph. D. Jack Silberman, an engineering lecturer at UC San Diego with over 20 years of industry experience in medtech, robotics, and biotech. The smart wheelchair project is providing our team opportunities for medical and robotics research in the area of Quality of Life (QOL) which will help them develop into professional engineers with applicable skills when they enter the job field while providing an open source hardware and software design.
